info.name: [Bible Brain] Example Workflows
info.description:
# Introduction 
These workflows are intended to document how a new developer would navigate the API to build an end-user application. 

Questions that we intend to answer here are:

How to find a Bible...
---
* in the Public Domain?
* available through the API Key?
* in a given language?
* with text or audio or dramatized audio or video

Once I have a Bible...
---
* how do I find the localized labels for books/chapters/verses?
* how do I find required copyright information?
* how do access content?

A note about the examples
---
Each request in the Example Workflow is part of a Postman Collection. When combined with an environment and an API key, the requests can be submitted and you will see live results. 
An API key is required for development and production use. However, sometimes you just want to get a feel for what the data looks like, and plan how you will interact with the data. For that use *only*, a generic API key is provided as part of the collection. This key is rate-limited to 1000 requests per month.

response.name: Alphabet Details (v4_alphabets.one)
response.body:
{ "data": { "script": "Adlm", "name": "Adlam", "unicode_pdf": null, "family": "African", "type": "alphabet", "white_space": "between words", "open_type_tag": "[none]", "complex_positioning": true, "requires_font": false, "unicode": true, "diacritics": true, "contextual_forms": true, "reordering": false, "case": null, "split_graphs": false, "status": "Current", "baseline": "bottom", "ligatures": "none", "direction": "rtl", "direction_notes": null, "sample": "", "sample_img": null, "description": "

The Adlam script is used for writing the Fulani language in Guinea. Prior to the creation of this script, the Fulani language was written in the Latin and Arabic scripts. In the 1980s, two teenage brothers, Ibrahima and Abdoulaye Barry, wondered why their language did not have its own script and set about creating one. They named their script ‘Adlam’ because the first four characters in the repertoire represent A, D, L, and M.

Following the creation of the script, the two brothers initially produced hand-written textbooks to aid in its dissemination. They first taught their other family members to read and write, then the women and children in their village. Along with the script, the books taught lessons in water hygiene and basic medical care. Gradually, the script grew in popularity and the brothers set up learning centres in Togo, Senegal, Benin, and even amongst Fulani speakers in New York. Eventually, the means were available to print the script, and a newspaper and a number of printed books were published. However, the rapid growth of Adlam attracted the attention of the Guinean government, who were opposed to the new script which they could not read, and Ibrahim was imprisoned for three months. After his release, in 2007, he moved to America and took a job with a software company. He used the expertise and financial savings he acquired there to create software for Adlam, and by 2012 three fonts and a keyboard had been created.

The script is written from right to left and letters can be joined to one another (cursive) or separate. There are 28 letters in all, and each letter has four forms, including upper- and lower-case forms. The script is an alphabet, with both consonant and vowel characters. Adlam also contains a set of digits from 0-9 and a number of diacritics for marking vowel length, gemination, and foreign sounds. The glottal stop is also indicated with a diacritic.

", "fonts": [], "languages": [], "bibles": [] } }

            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",

            "verse_start_alt": "12",
            "verse_end": 12,
            "verse_end_alt": "12",

            "verse_end": 13,

            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",

            "verse_end_alt": "15",

            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",

            "verse_end_alt": "16",

        {
            "book_id": "MAT",
            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 17,
            "verse_start_alt": "17",
            "verse_end": 17,
            "verse_end_alt": "17",
            "verse_text": "So all the generations from Abraham to David were fourteen generations, and from David to the deportation to Babylon fourteen generations, and from the deportation to Babylon to the Christ fourteen generations."

        {
            "book_id": "MAT",
            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 18,
            "verse_start_alt": "18",
            "verse_end": 18,
            "verse_end_alt": "18",
            "verse_text": "Now the birth of Jesus Christ took place in this way. When his mother Mary had been betrothed to Joseph, before they came together she was found to be with child from the Holy Spirit."

        {
            "book_id": "MAT",
            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 19,
            "verse_start_alt": "19",
            "verse_end": 19,
            "verse_end_alt": "19",
            "verse_text": "And her husband Joseph, being a just man and unwilling to put her to shame, resolved to divorce her quietly."
        },
        {
            "book_id": "MAT",
            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 20,
            "verse_start_alt": "20",
            "verse_end": 20,
            "verse_end_alt": "20",
            "verse_text": "But as he considered these things, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream, saying, “Joseph, son of David, do not fear to take Mary as your wife, for that which is conceived in her is from the Holy Spirit."
        },
        {
            "book_id": "MAT",
            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 21,
            "verse_start_alt": "21",
            "verse_end": 21,
            "verse_end_alt": "21",
            "verse_text": "She will bear a son, and you shall call his name Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins.”"
        },
        {
            "book_id": "MAT",
            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 22,
            "verse_start_alt": "22",
            "verse_end": 22,
            "verse_end_alt": "22",
            "verse_text": "All this took place to fulfill what the Lord had spoken by the prophet:"
        },
        {
            "book_id": "MAT",
            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 23,
            "verse_start_alt": "23",
            "verse_end": 23,
            "verse_end_alt": "23",
            "verse_text": "“Behold, the virgin shall conceive and bear a son, and they shall call his name Immanuel” (which means, God with us)."

            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 24,
            "verse_start_alt": "24",
            "verse_end": 24,
            "verse_end_alt": "24",
            "verse_text": "When Joseph woke from sleep, he did as the angel of the Lord commanded him: he took his wife,"

            "book_name": "Matthew",
            "book_name_alt": "Matthew",
            "chapter": 1,
            "chapter_alt": "1",
            "verse_start": 25,
            "verse_start_alt": "25",
            "verse_end": 25,
            "verse_end_alt": "25",

item.description:
A fileset uniquely identifies not only the Bible, but also the type of content available for that Bible. There are three main types of content: text, audio and video. 

Within each of these, there are further options for text formatting, optional background music on audio, and varying audio/video encoding bitrates and containers. 

The fileset should be used as the key for the bible/filesets endpoint. To determine which fileset to use, examine the "type", "size", "bitrate" and "container" values for a particular endpoint.

    },

item.description:
Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_Live_Streaming

HTTP Live Streaming (also known as HLS) is an HTTP-based adaptive bitrate streaming communications protocol developed by Apple Inc. and released in 2009. Support for the protocol is widespread in media players, web browsers, mobile devices, and streaming media servers. As of 2019, an annual video industry survey has consistently found it to be the most popular streaming format.[2] 

HLS resembles MPEG-DASH in that it works by breaking the overall stream into a sequence of small HTTP-based file downloads, each downloading one short chunk of an overall potentially unbounded transport stream. A list of available streams, encoded at different bit rates, is sent to the client using an extended M3U playlist.[3]

item.description:
Reference: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HTTP_Live_Streaming

HTTP Live Streaming (also known as HLS) is an HTTP-based adaptive bitrate streaming communications protocol developed by Apple Inc. and released in 2009. Support for the protocol is widespread in media players, web browsers, mobile devices, and streaming media servers. As of 2019, an annual video industry survey has consistently found it to be the most popular streaming format.[2] 

HLS resembles MPEG-DASH in that it works by breaking the overall stream into a sequence of small HTTP-based file downloads, each downloading one short chunk of an overall potentially unbounded transport stream. A list of available streams, encoded at different bit rates, is sent to the client using an extended M3U playlist.[3]

item.description:
Once you have identified a Bible, the next logical step is to find out common metadata about the Bible. Some of it is common, such as the books of the Bible, the chapters for each book, etc. Some of it is unique to a single Bible Translation, such as the copyright holder. When you signed up for a license key, you agreed to display the copyright information for any Bible content you deliver to your end users. 

Content Types
===
There are three primary types of content:
* text
* audio
* video

Generally speaking, if a Bible has audio, it also has text. And if a Bible has Video, it also has both text and audio. But there are some exceptions, notably related to Oral translations. Many languages have no written alphabet. There is much work in progress to translate from one Bible to another using only audio, without any written text. 

Note also that there are usually different copyright holders for the various content types. One group may have translated the Bible in text form, a second group may have recorded the audio based on the text, and a third group (usually Lumo Films) provides the video
